{    Rules 11 and 7 by Howard Schutzman    }
^-|CP||FP||AT|^B@2^z@3I|FP||AT|f the opponents play 4th best leads, you can often determine the distribution of the suit from the opening lead. The easiest case is when an opponent leads the 2, in which case, he must have a 4 card suit, since he has no lower cards. Similarly, if he leads a higher card, and you can see all the lower cards between you and dummy (for example, he leads the 5, and you can see the 4, 3, and 2), then he also has a 4 card suit. How does that help you? Well, if the opponents have 8 cards in the suit led, you know they are divided 4-4, so if you have a single stopper, there is no gain in holding up. Even if you cannot see all the cards below the suit led, you can often determine how the suit is divided. For example, if you are missing just one lower card in the suit led, the opponent has at most a 5 card suit, and if the other player plays that lower card, then you know the leader started with 4 cards in the suit.|
PG| ***** 216 ***** |


AT|

A rule that is sometimes useful when the opponents lead 4th best is known as the "|CP|8|FP|2|AT|Rule of 11|FP||CP||AT|". Let me explain the math behind it first. Given any card in a suit, because there are 13 cards in that suit, if you subtract the number of that card from 14, that tells you how many cards there are that are higher than that card. For example, with an 8, there are six higher cards (14 - 8 = 6), the A, K, Q, J, 10, and 9. Now if an opponent plays 4th best, you know he has 3 cards higher than the card led. Therefore, you can do some simple math to figure out how many higher cards are in the other 3 hands — 14 - 3 (number of higher in leader's hand) - the number of the card led. Since 14 -3 is always 11, if you subtract the number of the card led from 11, you can figure out how many higher cards there are in the remaining 3 hands.|
PG| ***** 217 ***** |


AT|

How can you apply that rule? Say, for example, your opponent leads the 8, and you know it is 4th best. Remember, I said there are six cards higher than the 8. The leader has 3 of them, and therefore the other 3 hands have the other 3 (and, indeed, 11 - 8 = 3). If between you and dummy, you have 3 cards higher than the 8, then the leader's partner has no cards higher than the 8. Similarly, if you and dummy have 2 cards higher than the 8, the leader's partner has one card higher. This information can often help you determine how the high cards are distributed, which increases the likelihood that you will play the suit to your best advantage. 
